-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Find the last three digits of 5¹⁰⁰ and add them; show that the sum equals 13. 2. [Key Idea] Work modulo 1000 (=8·125) and use the Chinese Remainder Theorem: (i) 5¹⁰⁰≡0 (mod 125), (ii) 5¹⁰⁰≡1 (mod 8). 3. [Proof] Step 1: Mod 125 Because 125=5³, 5¹⁰⁰ contains a factor 5¹⁰⁰⁻³ =5⁹⁷, so 5¹⁰⁰ ≡0 (mod 125). (1) Step 2: Mod 8 Observe 5²=25≡1 (mod 8), hence 5¹⁰⁰=(5²)⁵⁰≡1⁵⁰=1 (mod 8). (2) Step 3: Combine (1) and (2) Seek x such that x≡0 (mod 125), x≡1 (mod 8). Write x=125k. Substitute into the second congruence: 125k≡1 (mod 8) ⇒ 5k≡1 (mod 8) ⇒ k≡5 (mod 8) (since 5·5≡1). Take the smallest k=5; then x=125·5=625. Thus the last three digits of 5¹⁰⁰ are 625. Step 4: Digit sum 6+2+5 = 13. 4. [Conclusion] The final three digits of 5¹⁰⁰ are 625, whose digits sum to 13.
